rgh in 1952, helping us to see his later political achievements in a new light. It was after returning to Tanganyika that 'Mwalimu' (the teacher) formally entered politics, and led efforts to deliver Tanganyika to independence. Drawing on interviews with his contemporaries, as wellas archival sources, including his letters as a student and files that the colonial authorities kept on him, this revelatory and engaging account allows us to see Nyerere afresh. It also brings a new perspective on how the scholarship that Nyerere engaged with as a young man in Scotland influenced his ideas of the uhuru movement against colonial rule and, later, the ujamaa policy of African socialism that so defined his leadership of an independent Tanzania. Thomas Molony is Lecturer in African Studies at the University of Edinburgh.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aPresidentsvBiographyzTanzania. 4aAfrican Studies. 4aPolitics & Economics. 7aHISTORY / Africa / General.2bisacsh  aAfrican Socialism.  aAfrican political studies.  aAfrican studies.  aBiography.  aEarly Life.  aIndependence.  aJulius Kambarage Nyerere.  aScotland.  aTanganyika.  aTanzania's First President.  aTanzania.  aUhuru Movement.  aUjamaa Policy.  abiography.  acolonialism.  aleadership.  apolitical freedom.  apolitical independence.  apolitical science.  apresident of Tanzania.  arevolution.  asocialism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2014z978311143136940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781782042952?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781782042952423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781782042952/original  a978-3-11-143136-9  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2014b2014  aGBV-deGruyter-alles